Idioms, phrasal verbs, and figurative language.

Everything so far has made your English correct, precise, well shaped, and well pitched. This notebook adds the last thing. Making it sound native, rather than assembled. The mark of figurative language is that its meaning is not the sum of its words. To bite the bullet has nothing to do with bullets. And English is saturated with this. Strip it out, and your English is flawless, yet somehow foreign. The textbook never quite leaves.

A fair warning up front. This is the layer where overreach backfires hardest. A misused idiom, or a mangled metaphor, jars far more than the plain sentence it replaced. It announces non-native louder than a small grammar slip. So the goal here is natural, not more. Which is why two of the five parts are about restraint.

Phrasal verbs. The everyday workhorse.

A phrasal verb is a verb plus a particle. Give up. Put off. Run into. It is the engine of natural spoken English, and natives reach for it far more than its single, formal cousin. The particle changes everything. Listen to the verb give, with different particles. Give up means quit. Give in means surrender. Give out means distribute, or stop working. Give away means donate, or reveal. And give off means emit. One verb, five meanings, set entirely by the particle.

Now, register, from notebook six. The phrasal verb is the neutral, spoken option. Its single latinate verb is the formal twin, which is notebook two's two vocabularies again. Put off, or postpone. Find out, or discover. Look into, or investigate. Go up, or increase. Speech leans phrasal. Formal writing leans latinate. Compare. The stiff version. I will investigate the issue and we can discuss it. The natural, spoken version. I'll look into it and we can talk it over.

There is one grammar trap. The pronoun rule. With separable phrasal verbs, a pronoun must sit inside. You say, turn it off, not, turn off it. A full noun can go on either side. Turn off the light, or turn the light off, are both fine.

Here is the strategy. Do not memorise lists. Learn a handful of high-frequency ones deeply, in real sentences. Depth beats breadth. The verbs get, put, take, come, and go, alone, spawn dozens you will actually use.

Idioms. Use only what you have truly heard.

An idiom is a fixed expression whose meaning is not its literal words. To bite the bullet means to do the unpleasant but necessary thing. Stick to high-frequency, living ones, and skip the museum pieces, like raining cats and dogs. A few useful ones. To play it by ear means to decide as you go. To be on the same page means to be in agreement. To touch base means to check in briefly. A grey area is something unclear. Back to the drawing board means to start over. A blessing in disguise is a hidden upside. To cut corners is to do something cheaply or poorly. And to get to the point means to stop stalling.

Three rules govern them. First, they are frozen. You cannot swap the words. It is spill the beans, not spill the peas. It is the ball is in your court, not in your field. Second, they carry register. Mostly informal and spoken, and rare in formal writing, as notebook six warned. Third, they are culture-bound. Many come from sport or sailing, and may baffle international listeners.

Now, the big trap. Half-remembering. A mangled idiom is worse than plain words, because it flags non-native loudly. A blessing in disguise becomes, wrongly, a blessing in the sky. For all intents and purposes becomes, wrongly, for all intensive purposes. So the rule is strict. Use only idioms you have actually heard, kept intact. Unsure of a single word? Then do not use it. An idiom is like an inside joke that a whole language shares. Natural when you land it exactly, and awkward the moment you fumble the punchline.

Metaphor and simile. Making the abstract concrete.

Figurative comparison turns something abstract into something you can picture. A simile is an explicit comparison, using like or as. It landed like a punch. Busy as a bee. A metaphor is an implicit one, saying X simply is Y. Time is money. She's a rock. A flood of emails.

Now, here is something to notice. You already swim in dead, or conventional, metaphors, without realising it. And that is good. It is just normal English. You grasp an idea. A deadline is looming. You are drowning in work. You talk about the heart of the matter, or a key point. Native English is built from these.

Fresh metaphors add vividness and voice, and notebook eight turns them into a tool of persuasion. But they carry more risk. Two dangers. First, mixed metaphors. Two clashing images in one breath. We'll burn that bridge when we come to it. Or, it's not rocket surgery. Open one picture, and finish it in the same picture. One image per sentence. Second, clichés. These are metaphors worn smooth. Think outside the box. Low-hanging fruit. Move the needle. So overused that they now signal empty corporate noise. Fresh, or plain, both beat tired.

Sounding un-translated.

Why does correct English still sometimes sound foreign? Usually because it was translated word by word from a first language, or assembled logically, rather than reached for as a ready-made native chunk.

Three things to hold onto. First, idioms do not port. A literal translation of your first-language expression produces something English speakers simply do not say. The image that is vivid at home lands as a riddle here. Second, natives store chunks, not words. This is notebook two's collocation, again. Make a decision. Take a break. By and large. As far as I'm concerned. They retrieve whole phrases, not individual bricks. Third, here is the test. Does a native actually say this, in this exact combination? If you built it by logic, but never heard it, be suspicious.

And here is the key insight. The path is input, not rules. There is no formula for what sounds natural. Only exposure, plus attention. Read and listen to real English, notice the chunks that keep recurring, store them whole, and reuse them intact. Recognition comes before production. You should have heard an idiom many times before you ever deploy it. This layer is grown, not memorised.

When not to reach for it.

Because overreach costs the most here, restraint is its own skill. Hold back in four situations. First, when the register is formal, as notebook six taught. Idioms and slangy phrasal verbs are wrong in a legal notice, a formal report, or an academic paper. Those want the plain or latinate twin. You say, we'll look into it, in chat, but, we will investigate the matter, in the report. Second, when the audience is international. With non-native listeners, idioms reduce clarity. Plain English reaches more people, and dropping the idiom is the considerate choice, not the lazy one. Third, when you are not fully sure. If the exact form or meaning is shaky, use the plain version. A clean plain sentence always beats a broken idiom. Fourth, when you are already using one. One apt idiom lands. A paragraph stuffed with them reads like a phrasebook showing off. Idiom is seasoning, not the meal.

So here is the principle. Idiom should feel inevitable, not inserted. If you are reaching for one mainly to sound advanced, which is the same trap notebooks two and six flagged, that is exactly the moment to choose the plain word instead.

To finish, the notebook gives you a mix of tasks. Make a stiff sentence natural with phrasal verbs, fix a mangled idiom, fix a mixed metaphor, choose an idiom that fits a situation, and spot where an idiom does not belong. Compare with the suggested answers afterward. Yours need not match. If it sounds like something a native would actually say, and it fits the room, you have got it.
